<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="play">
<PB N="1" REF="3">
<HEAD>ZORINSKI: <HI>A PLAY</HI> IN THREE ACTS.</HEAD>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="act">
<HEAD>ACT 1.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE 1.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">CRACOW&mdash;<HI>a View of the</HI> DIET&mdash;<HI>Bells ringing&mdash;a number of People di&s;covered, among them</HI> RADZANO <HI>di&s;gui&s;ed.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE>ENTER WHITSKI.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Whit&s;ki.</SPEAKER>
<P>MAKE way there for the King&mdash;here he comes&mdash;here comes the great Ca&s;imir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rad.</SPEAKER>
<P>That &s;lave I do remember&mdash;&s;ave thee, fellow!&mdash;who&s;e va&s;&s;al art thou?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>Marry, courteous &s;tranger, I tend the mill of the Lord Rodom&s;ko, Ca&s;tellan of Wounitz, here in Cracovia.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rad.</SPEAKER>
<P>Remembere&s;t thou the Lord Radzano?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>Remember him&mdash;alack! the day&mdash;the la&s;t time I beheld his gallant form, was on the battle|ments
<PB N="2" REF="4">
of his ca&s;tle&mdash;then a very &s;tripling&mdash;when my pre&s;ent Lord be&s;ieged it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rad.</SPEAKER>
<P>So then, Radzano was by force expelled&mdash;pry'thee the &s;tory.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>If this addle pate of mine play me no trick, marry, thus it was&mdash;during the troubles of the late reign&mdash;peaceful right was elbow'd out by warlike might&mdash;then Rodom&s;ko our pre&s;ent Lord, taking 'vantage of the time, when our troops were on the frontier, tugging with the common enemy, made inroad on us: On this, Radzano hied him back to his ca&s;tle; but, alack! might cuffed down right, and, in the encounter, our good and brave lord was &s;lain&mdash;Ah! &s;tranger, that was a grievous day.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rad.</SPEAKER>
<P>So&mdash;I &s;till am lord then of my va&s;&s;als hearts.&mdash;Fellow, I thank thee for thy &s;tory; a day may come when I'll requite thy love for thy lo&s;t lord&mdash;but &s;oft, the King.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, here he comes&mdash;&s;o maje&s;tic, and yet &s;o humble; &s;o ju&s;t; and yet &s;o merciful&mdash;the benizon of heaven light on him! he's the poor man's friend.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rad. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Shewing a paper)</STAGE>
<P>If thy report be true, the wrongs here written, may meet atonement&mdash;&s;tand back; he approaches.</P>
</SP>
<Q><PB N="3" REF="5">
<TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Chorus of Pea&s;ants.</SPEAKER>
<L>HAIL! mighty King!</L>
<L>'Tis love that elevates our &s;trains,</L>
<L>'Tis joy the &s;welling note &s;u&s;tains,</L>
<L>To thee we call,</L>
<L>Welcome as the God of day,</L>
<L>Who pours his animating ray</L>
<L>Alike on all.</L>
<L>Hail! mighty King!</L>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<STAGE>During the Chorus, Guards, Officers, and Nobles enter in Proce&s;&s;ion&mdash;at the conclu&s;on, the King, Cardinal, and Nobles.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;imir </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(to the Cardinal)</STAGE>
<P>By my faith! well, urged&mdash;Lord Cardinal your words befit as well the objects of true policy, as they attune with the holy mandate of your calling. Yes! our country &s;hall have peace! true; the&s;e Teutonic Knights have di&s;graced their order, turning from chri&s;|tian &s;ervice and true chivalry, to deeds of u&s;urpa|tion and dominion! yet nerved, tho' we are to check the&s;e ravagers; it befits us rather with firm expo&s;tulation to meet our enemy than ri&s;k our &s;ubjects blood in keen encounter&mdash;let conquerors a&s;tound the ear with the din of war, the trumpets clangor, and the groans of captives&mdash;be mine the clamours of my people's love.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="4" REF="6"><HI>As the King pa&s;&s;es on,</HI> RADZANO <HI>kneels</HI>&mdash;CASIMIR <HI>takes the Petition&mdash;looks at it&mdash;&s;tops &s;uddenly, and with &s;crutinizing eye, examines</HI> RADZANO&mdash;<HI>approaches him.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(in a low tone.)</STAGE>
<P>Radzano?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rad.</SPEAKER>
<P>He.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Amazement!&mdash;my good Lords proceed you to the Diet. <STAGE>(Exeunt Lords. He waves his hand to the people, who exeunt).</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rad.</SPEAKER>
<P>My gracious King!<STAGE>(kneels.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ri&s;e to my heart&mdash;&s;ay, what fair fortune has pre&s;erved thee to me&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rad.</SPEAKER>
<P>A woman good, my liege, and fair as fortune e'er was pictured, yet, in &s;ooth, without her ficklene&s;s; and only blind in her fond love of me. My King may well remember when I left the embattled frontier.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Remember it! by my &s;word, I had rea|&s;on; for with thee went this body's buckler&mdash;oh my be&s;t &s;oldier&mdash;'twas this arm fir&s;t taught thee the rudiments of war, when &s;carcely truncheon high; but my love breaks in upon thy &s;tory&mdash;on&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rad.</SPEAKER>
<P>I reached my ca&s;tle time enough to &s;ee its ruin&mdash;Rodom&s;ko triumphed. In a remote apartment, con&s;tructed for concealment, I lay hid, hoping for life and better days; that apart|ment was &s;elected for Rodom&s;ko's daughter, the beauteous Ro&s;olia, to her pitying ear I told my &s;tory; and her &s;oft bo&s;om, rich in nature's be&s;t
<PB N="5" REF="7">
endowments, &s;oon matured compa&s;&s;ion into love. At a fit time I fled.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Whither, good Radzano?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rad.</SPEAKER>
<P>To England, my loved Lord; there I &s;ojourned till fame proudly proclaimed, that ju&s;|tice was again enthroned in Poland, for there reigned great Ca&s;imir; for that ju&s;tice thus I bend my knee! and my boon is, that my tongue may denounce Rodom&s;ko, villain! and my good &s;word avenge my wrongs.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then, I refu&s;e thy boon.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rad.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dread liege! heaven will make the good cau&s;e pro&s;perous!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Radzano, link not heaven with murder!&mdash;if heaven recognized the &s;word's arbitrament, Rodom&s;ko ne'er had triumphed&mdash;droop not my friend&mdash;by my crown thou &s;halt have ju&s;tice!&mdash;even now in angry parle I meet Rodom&s;ko! the&s;e hot lords, who live but in a &s;torm, urge me to renew the war&mdash;but of that hereafter&mdash;uncloud thee&mdash;be thy&s;elf&mdash;attend me at the Diet&mdash;once more Radzano, welcome!</P>
<STAGE>Exeunt,</STAGE>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="scene">
<PB N="6" REF="8">
<HEAD>SCENE II.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">Draws and di&s;covers the Country near <HI>CRACOW&mdash;RACHEL</HI> and Slaves at work.</HEAD>
<STAGE>Enter AMALEKITE&mdash;<HI>the Slaves bow.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ama.</SPEAKER>
<P>Again, again, dat i&s;h goot&mdash;now vork you damned Poli&s;h dogs! or ba&s;tinodo's the vord. Rachel; come here you &s;lut&mdash;you auda|cious&mdash;delicious little tit&mdash; <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE> Come here, I &s;ay. <STAGE>(angrily)</STAGE> Mu&s;t &s;peak cro&s;s befores dem&mdash;but my pretty plump cherry, I be's not angry.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rac.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Sir! then what makes you look &s;o terrible?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ama.</SPEAKER>
<P>It's the mild tender pa&s;&s;ion of love&mdash; <STAGE>(with amorous fervor)</STAGE> You know, Rachel, 'twas for your &s;ake, I did not turn your fader Wit&s;ki, out of his mill to &s;tarve, tho' he dare laugh at me&mdash;me, Amalekite Grabow&s;ki, chief agent to Lord Rodom&s;ko&mdash;Ca&s;tellan of Wounitz in Cracovia; &s;o you &s;ees how I loves you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rac.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! I'm &s;ure you dont; for lovers &s;igh, and kneel, and&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ama.</SPEAKER>
<P>Kneel; oh, dear! I cannot do's dat&mdash;what a pity's love is &s;uch a foe to dignity! I &s;ay, Rachel; <STAGE>(looks to &s;ee whether the pea&s;ants ob&s;erve him)</STAGE> I &s;ay&mdash;how do you contrive to have &s;o &s;oft a hand? <STAGE>(enter Wit&s;ki)</STAGE> I &s;hould &s;uppo&s;e, labours would
<PB N="7" REF="9">
make it hard; <STAGE>(fumbling and ki&s;&s;ing it)</STAGE> but I de|clare its as &s;mooth and as &s;oft&mdash;ble&s;s my &s;oul&mdash; <STAGE>(during this, Wit&s;ki advances, bows low and clo&s;e to Ama. who, by accident, lays his hand on his head)</STAGE> Oh Lud! vat i&s;h dat&mdash;&s;tand off.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>You know, Sir, you always told me to &s;hew you homage.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ama.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes&punc; but at an awful di&s;tance.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>True; but &s;eeing your honour &s;o clo&s;e to my daughter, I thought I might be treated in the family way. <STAGE>(laughs a&s;ide).</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ama.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now he's grinning again! I Rachel had behaved ill, &s;o I was puni&s;hing her&mdash;vas not I puni&s;hing you young vomans?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rac.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, indeed you were, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ama.</SPEAKER>
<P>Go to work, Hu&s;&s;ey! So Witzki, you've been at Cracow.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, your honour; and here is the produce of the flour for our Lord&mdash; <STAGE>(gives a pur&s;e)</STAGE> and here you know Sir, is the&mdash;for the &s;teward. <STAGE>(gives another.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ama. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(putting one in each pocket)</STAGE>
<P>Yes! Yes! dat i&s;h vary goot&mdash;vare you going?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>Home to my wife.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ama. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(turning quick round)</STAGE>
<P>!Ah! how does &s;he do? &s;he's a very pretty little vomans!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>My wife too! was there ever &s;uch an old&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Q'Curragh </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(without)</STAGE>
<P>Hollo!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="8" REF="10"><HI>Enter</HI> O'CURRAGH.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray is there ever a Jew faced creature?<STAGE>(Wit&s;ki points to Amalekite&mdash;and exit)</STAGE> pray Mr. Jew, is your chri&s;tian name Amalekite?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ama.</SPEAKER>
<P>Amalekite i&s;h my name.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then how are you? how are you?<STAGE>(Amalekite in action, demands obei&s;ance)</STAGE> Well, I'll indulge you&mdash;there&mdash; <STAGE>(bows)</STAGE> but you might have the civility to return it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ama.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'm in office!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>And I &s;uppo&s;e like other great men, you have &s;tooped &s;o low to get there, that your back has been cramped ever &s;ince; but come to bu&s;ine&s;s&mdash;look there&mdash; <STAGE>(&s;hews a letter)</STAGE> and be &s;e|cret, &s;nug&mdash;dumb as a potatoe.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ama. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(reads)</STAGE>
<P>"Your Lord Radzano greets you"&mdash;holy Abraham! is he alive?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hu&s;h!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ama.</SPEAKER>
<P><Q>Your Lord Radzano greets you, e'en now he is arrived in Cracow, to claim his rights, and cru&s;h that u&s;urper Rodom&s;ko</Q>&mdash;ble&s;s my &s;oul!&mdash;<Q>do you win the va&s;&s;als to his intere&s;t&mdash;he who brings this will in&s;truct you further; be faithful, and you will be rewarded. RADZANO.</Q></P>
<P>Ble&s;s my &s;oul, what &s;hall I do? Radzano has the right; but then Rodom&s;ko has the po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion&mdash;
<PB N="9" REF="11">
ble&s;s my con&s;cience, what &s;hall I do? then Rad|zano is in great favour with the King&mdash;ble&s;s my con&s;cience, what &s;hall I do? but then Rodom&s;ko is in great favour with the nobility&mdash;ble&s;s my con|&s;cience, what &s;hall I do?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who comes here?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ama.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stand a&s;ide&mdash;it is the Lord Rodom&s;ko, who pa&s;&s;es here in his way to the Diet&mdash;&s;tand a&s;ide.</P>
<STAGE>(puts up the letter, and O'Curragh retires.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> RODOMSKO <HI>and Train</HI>&mdash;AMALEKITE <HI>bows very low&mdash;the Slaves pro&s;trate them&s;elves.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ama.</SPEAKER>
<P>Heaven &s;ave our gracious Lord!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha&s;t thou ought to impart?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ama.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nothing, dread Lord.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Are the &s;laves obedient?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ama.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, dread Lord.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>On to Cracow.</P>
<STAGE>Exeunt Rodom&s;ko and train.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(comes forward)</STAGE>
<P>I &s;ay, this Lord Ro|dom&s;ko is a &s;tiff crabbed kind of a&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ama.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! he keeps the &s;laves in proper &s;ub|jections.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>Proper &s;ubjection! I'll tell you what, he appears to me like the great tall thi&s;tle in the po|tatoe garden, which bothers every one who touches it, and prevents the humble fruit from arriving at the whole&s;ome maturity nature intended. Oh! I wi&s;h I had the docking of him&mdash;now my Lord
<PB N="10" REF="12">
Radzano is &s;o humane, &s;o poli&s;hed, &s;o&mdash;gallant&mdash;&s;o&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ama.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hah! hah! I &s;uppo&s;e he has brought over with him what will plea&s;e the ladies.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>Faith! you may &s;ay that, for he has brought me over with him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ama.</SPEAKER>
<P>And I hope he is ho&s;pitable and charit|able, and all&mdash;that damned &s;tuff! <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! he has been &s;ucking in the breath of it in little England, Mr. Amalekite. Oh! confound your name; could not they have called you Nebuchadnezzar, or Mac Laughlin, or O'Shaughne&s;&s;y, or any ea&s;y agreeable name of that &s;ort&mdash;Oh! we &s;hall have &s;uch jolly doings; every heart will wear the face of joy, and all coun|tenances, men, women, cows, Jews, and &s;heep, mu&s;t all be on the broad grin.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ama.</SPEAKER>
<P>I mu&s;t con&s;ider&mdash;which of my Lords &s;hall I betray?&mdash;ble&s;s my con&s;cience&mdash;&s;laves treat this &s;tranger with all re&s;pect, and give him the &s;ong of welcome&mdash;you will follow me. It's a very, puzzling ca&s;e; Radzano has the right&mdash;Rodom&s;ko has&mdash;ble&s;s my con&s;cience!</P>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Slaves approach and pro&s;trate them&s;elves to</HI> O'CURRAGH.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thank you, thank you! oh! low enough in con&s;cience&mdash;what are you at? what are you at jewels?&mdash;keep your fore paws off the ground, and dont make bulls of your&s;elves&mdash;&s;tand
<PB N="11" REF="13">
up I &s;ay&mdash;Heaven never meant its own image &s;hould be &s;o degraded!</P>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>SONG&mdash;</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RACHEL&mdash;</SPEAKER>
<LG>
<L>Courteous &s;tranger,</L>
<L>Now free from danger,</L>
<L>And laughing at departed care and labour,</L>
<L>Thy cares unbending,</L>
<L>Thy journey ending,</L>
<L>Now fri&s;k it to the merry pipe and tabor,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2">
<HEAD>II</HEAD>
<L>Welcome &s;tranger, welcome here,</L>
<L>An humble welcome but &s;incere;</L>
<L>From the lowly &s;laves receive</L>
<L>All, alas! they have to give.</L>
<L>Courteous &s;tranger, &amp;c.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3">
<HEAD>III.</HEAD>
<L>May the &s;avage bea&s;t of prey,</L>
<L>Ne'er cro&s;s thee on thy lonely way,</L>
<L>And, returning, may'&s;t thou find,</L>
<L>Thy friend &s;incere, thy mi&s;tre&s;s kind.</L>
<L>Courteous &s;tranger, &amp;c.</L>
</LG>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<STAGE>Exeunt different &s;ides.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE III.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub"><HI>The</HI> DIET.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>The KING, (&s;eated)</HI> CARDINAL, RODOMSKO, <HI>Nobles, &amp;c.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>In pur&s;uance of our purpo&s;e, we have ap|pointed my Lord Cardinal our amba&s;&s;ador, to conclude a peace with the Teutonick Knights.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="12" REF="14">
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Peace! Is then a &s;oldier, the world's right arm, to wither and decay, that hordes of prie&s;ts, with their beads and cro&s;iers, may preach us into cowards? but I wonder not! for &s;ince the great Zorin&s;ki was di&s;graced&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>What of him?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>He was hone&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>He was proud and inflexible! but forbear to name him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Since, Sire, you have bani&s;hed from your councils tho&s;e hardy &s;pirits, who alone were fit to aid the public weal, naught now will down but peace&mdash;<Q>the general good&mdash;the&s;e are the entrap|ping blandi&s;hments held out, for emancipating &s;laves, privileging towns, and u&s;ing every cir|cumventive art to cru&s;h the power of the nobi|lity!&mdash;peace! let my Lord Cardinal preach its ble&s;&s;ings&mdash;I hate it!</Q> What gentlemen of Po|land &s;hall your goodly cimeters canker in their &s;heaths, while tho&s;e u&s;urping Knights de&s;poil your borders?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(coming forward)</STAGE>
<P>Fiery Lord! hear me. If it be my duty to root out u&s;urpation and foul con&s;piracy, why need I wage the war on Pomo|rania's borders, when my eye's &s;cope compre|hends an object that would give vengeance full employment?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sire! Rodom&s;ko &s;corns ba&s;e fear! nor will he &s;hun enquiry&mdash;thou would'&s;t demand, how
<PB N="13" REF="15">
came I by my power; my an&s;wer is, by valour|ous achievement&mdash;by conque&s;t&mdash;the &s;oldier's te|nure! but why wa&s;te we words? Radzano being dead&mdash;who is there?&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(holds up his finger)</STAGE>
<P>Indeed!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> RADZANO.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lightnings bla&s;t him!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Behold the wronged Radzano! what can'&s;t thou urge?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>I cannot battle it with words&mdash;'twas this good arm that gave me power; 'tis this good arm that will maintain it!&mdash;follow me&mdash;thou wilt not find it pal&s;ied, boy.</P>
<STAGE>(both going)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>On your allegiance, hold!&mdash;&s;till the friend to gentle peace; &s;till anxious to pre&s;erve the mo&s;t rebellious drop of &s;ubjects blood&mdash;let me propo&s;e between you terms, where love may grow, and honour ratify them. Rodom&s;ko, Radzano loves thy daughter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let her be mediatrix between you; let holy marriage with their hands unite your hearts; &s;o live in equal power and love&mdash;what &s;ays Rad|zano?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rad.</SPEAKER>
<P>My King has &s;poken my &s;oul's fonde&s;t hope!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE>
<P>Hold&mdash;hold&mdash;this marriage has &s;ome promi&s;e in't&mdash;it gives Radzano to my
<PB N="14" REF="16">
power&mdash;and &s;hould the confederate Lords&mdash;it &s;hall be &s;o.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>That &s;cowling brow looks not con&s;ent.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rad.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then, my liege, it wrongs my heart! Tis true, I have not that April face that clouds and &s;hines at every gu&s;t of grief or joy; but 'tis my rugged nature;&mdash;I pray you bear with it. Radzano! here's my hand.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rad. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(pre&s;&s;ing it to his bo&s;om)</STAGE>
<P>Thus let it &s;tamp upon my heart a &s;on's obedience; and to oblivion give each ho&s;tile thought!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Rodom&s;ko, hie you to your ca&s;tle; for e'en this night in per&s;on we will progre&s;s thither, and con&s;ummate this happy union.</P>
<STAGE>(Rod. bows)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE>
<P>So&mdash;then a Lord of Poland, great in birth and arms, pre&s;erves his dignities, by the arch dimples of a puling, girl&mdash;Oh Cupid! how I honour thee!</P>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Radzano! let me pour into thy brea&s;t my griefs&mdash;the wrongs I bear from the&s;e injurious lords pre&s;s hard upon me! but I am rich in poor men's prayers, and that's a kingly &s;olace. Oh, I would ri&s;e unto my people, like the god of day to Lapland's icy &s;ons, after his wintry ab&s;ence! What, not a word Radzano? I &s;ee the lover dulls the patriot&mdash;but I forgive it&mdash;away to thy Ro|&s;olia&mdash;yet mark her father&mdash;watch well Ro|dom&s;ko&mdash;e'en now con&s;piracy's at work again&s;t my throne and&mdash;per&s;on: yet &s;pite of impending
<PB N="15" REF="17">
death I'll on!&mdash;farewel! my friend. <STAGE>(Radzano bows, and exit.)</STAGE> My good Lords attend me! Oh my country! let me but &s;ave thee&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>Exeunt.</STAGE>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="4" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE IV.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">&mdash;RODOMSKO'S <HI>Ca&s;tle.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> RODOMSKO, <HI>reading a Letter.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P><Q>The Confederates greet thee, brave Ro|dom&s;ko; if they have appeared inactive, 'twas as nature &s;tilly pau&s;ing, before the coming &s;torm; for 'tis re&s;olved that Ca&s;imir &s;hall fall.</Q> Ven|geance, I thank thee! <Q>Forty cho&s;en men are ready for the achievement, waiting but a leader&mdash;know, Rodom&s;ko, in thy mines dwells a man fa&s;hioned to conduct the daring enterprize&mdash;&s;eek him in&s;tantly&mdash;the brave fellow who brings this, by who&s;e dejected brow thou'lt &s;ee he's ripe for murder, will conduct thee to the man we &s;eek&mdash;farewel! and triumph.</Q>&mdash;Now tremble, Ca&s;imir&mdash;But &s;oft, the&mdash;me&s;&s;enger from the Lords approaches&mdash;what &s;ays my letter?<STAGE>(enter O'Curragh, &s;miling)</STAGE> dejected brow! if the mind's con&s;truction be indexed in the face, this man bears &s;weet content about him&mdash;Health to thee, friend!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE>
<P>Mighty civil however.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="16" REF="18">
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>In&s;truct me in your fortunes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, my hi&s;tory?&mdash;Oh! I'll tell yotur Lord&s;hip; and a &s;weet piece of geography it is&mdash;The fir&s;t thing I know is, that I don't know where I was born, for nobody could tell me; and being young my&s;elf at the time, it has &s;lipped my memory.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Shallow babler!&mdash;thy name?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>O'Curragh, the faithful &s;ervant of Lord Radzano.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(with irritation)</STAGE>
<P>Com'&s;t thou from him? well&mdash;well&mdash;what of him?&mdash;di&s;patch&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>He &s;ent me his humble &s;ervant to ex|pre&s;s his &s;orrow, that he can't, where he is, throw him&s;elf at the feet of the fair Ro&s;olia. I make his excu&s;es clum&s;ily; but were he here him&s;elf, he'd make a much better apology for his ab&s;ence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Begone, fellow!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have the plea&s;ure to take my leave. Oh! how my ma&s;ter &s;ighs&mdash;and then he clo&s;es his eyes, and looks &s;o tenderly&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Away! I &s;ay&mdash;that gallery leads to my daughter's apartment&mdash;prattle the&s;e gewgaws there&mdash;each mawki&s;h nothing will, on her love-&s;ick ta&s;te, drop &s;weet as Hybla's honey.&mdash;Away!&mdash; <STAGE>(exit O'Curragh)</STAGE> for here comes one who embo|dies well the picture given.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> NACLO.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nac.</SPEAKER>
<P>The confederated Lords greet thee.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="17" REF="19">
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thou art welcome!&mdash;approach&mdash;nearer&mdash;nearer&mdash;know'&s;t thou the drift of this?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nac.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, dread Lord!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then bring me to him we &s;eek&mdash;yet hold, tell me the manner of the man, that I may better wind about his heart, and trap him to my purpo&s;e; is he&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nac.</SPEAKER>
<P>By turns, my Lord, every thing&mdash;&s;ome|times, mocking the horror of his fate, he out toils the &s;lave, anon he &s;tarts from his labour, and with indignation gra&s;ps his &s;pade, as 'twere the &s;ceptre that &s;wayed the world. The fooli&s;h knaves in the mine &s;ay, that love hath crazed him; but, to my thinking, he re&s;embles more the hungry vulture than the &s;orrowing dove.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>The picture's big with promi&s;e; conduct me to him&mdash;how &s;hall I be&s;t approach him? nay, prythee lead;&mdash;'tis &s;trange!</P>
<STAGE>Exeunt, ruminating, Naclo leads.</STAGE>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="5" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE V.&mdash;<HI>The Country.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> O'CURRAGH.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>Upon my honour, this Lady Ro&s;olia is a bewitching creature! and now that &s;he has pa&s;&s;ed the ordeal of con&s;tancy, which is, by looking me over without &s;o much as an ogle at me&mdash;why my
<PB N="18" REF="20">
ma&s;ter may call him&s;elf a happy man. I don't know how it is, but I think this &s;nug agreeable per&s;on of mine is a &s;ort of a female te&s;t; ju&s;t like a bit of rough gla&s;s that they try money on&mdash;and have you found any&mdash;bad ones O'Curragh? oh! &s;weet Mrs. Flannigan for that&mdash;never &s;hall I forget!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>SONG&mdash;</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'CURRAGH,</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(At the dead of the night.)</STAGE>
<LG>
<L>AT the dead of the night, when by whi&s;ky in&s;pired,</L>
<L>And pretty Katty Flannigan, my &s;en&s;es had fired,</L>
<L>I tapped at her window, when thus &s;he began,</L>
<L>Oh! what the devil are you at?&mdash;get out you naughty man.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2">
<HEAD>II.</HEAD>
<L>I gave her a look, oh, as &s;ly as a thief,</L>
<L>Or when hungry, I'd view a fine furloin of beef:</L>
<L>My heart is red hot, &s;ays I, but cold is my &s;kin,</L>
<L>So pretty Mrs. Flannigan&mdash;oh, won't you let me in?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3">
<HEAD>III.</HEAD>
<L>She opening the door, I &s;at down by the fire,</L>
<L>And &s;oon was relieved from the wet, cold and mire.</L>
<L>And I plea&s;ed her &s;o mightily, that, e'er it was day,</L>
<L>I &s;tole poor Katty's tender heart, and &s;o tripped away.</L>
</LG>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thinking of old times has given me &s;uch a comical feel, that if any pretty creature was to come acro&s;s me, I fancy I &s;hould be rather
<PB N="19" REF="21">
agreeable company. In faith, you are in luck O'Curragh, for here comes that delicious mor&s;el, that &s;ung her Poli&s;h planxty &s;o &s;weetly.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> RACHEL.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rac.</SPEAKER>
<P>Heigh! ho! where can my dear Zarno tarry &s;o long! he knows I have but an hour from work, and yet he is not come. <STAGE>(&s;eeing O'Curragh, bows)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>Bend not to me &s;weet one; rather let me kneel to you&mdash;you ladies are the Lords of the creation. <STAGE>(kneels)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ZARNO&mdash;<HI>&s;tarts.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Rachel! <STAGE>(Rachel runs to Zarno and em|braces him)</STAGE> how dare you in&s;ult my Rachel! &s;he's mine, alone mine&mdash;I love her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then &s;he's alone mine too, for I love her!&mdash;and if I've in&s;ulted her, I flatter my&s;elf I can give her &s;atisfaction&mdash;In&s;ult! I don't like that; pray, Sir, would you ju&s;t &s;tep a&s;ide, and conde&s;cend to explain that word in&s;ult?&mdash;here's the prettie&s;t chopper of logic&mdash; <STAGE>(pointing to his &s;word)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>I under&s;tand you, but I dare not.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dare not, you paltry&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hear me&mdash;not for my&s;elf I fear, but for her: &s;hould a freeman be killed in a &s;lave's quar|rel, &s;he would &s;uffer, &s;he would be puni&s;hed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="20" REF="22">
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>In love with the girl, and yet for her &s;ake dares not defend her&mdash;that's hard! that's hard! but can't we manage it any how?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes! if you're a man; conceal our cau&s;e of quarrel, and I'll &s;hew you what I dare&mdash;I can find a &s;word.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>Poor, fellow! oh! what a plea&s;ure it will be to fight him&mdash;Upon my honour, our cau&s;e of di&s;pute &s;hall be a &s;ecret.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thank you, thank you; come along&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rac.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! pray don't quarrel, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>Quarrel! not at all; not the lea&s;t ani|mo&s;ity&mdash;If I &s;hould kill him, I'll give you leave to ax him whether I did it in pa&s;&s;ion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rac.</SPEAKER>
<P>But why fight at all?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>Upon my con&s;cience, I can't immedi|ately tell why we fight&mdash;Oh! it's for your &s;ake&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rac.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall hate you!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hate me! upon my honour, I'm &s;o unu&s;ed to hear a woman &s;ay that, that it con|fu&s;es&mdash;oh, this head! this head! what am I at?&mdash;going to kill a man about a woman that don't care for me?&mdash;come here, come here: there, my dear boy, there's &s;atisfaction! <STAGE>(joins their hands.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>You're a generous fellow!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>But why dont you marry?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="21" REF="23">
<SPEAKER>Rac.</SPEAKER>
<P>Becau&s;e I am a &s;lave; and Zarno can't afford to buy me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>Buy you!&mdash;upon my con&s;cience, I &s;hould like to buy a flock of &s;uch pet lambs&mdash;<Q>but as you both &s;eem tolerably built for run|ning, why don't you trot off in a canter?</Q></P>
</SP>
<Q><SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Becau&s;e, if Rachel were taken, her lord would kill her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then he'd be hanged for it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah! no. I have heard there was a good law once, that made a Lord pay a fine for killing a man, but it's never put in force now.</P>
</SP></Q>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>"O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P><Q>A fine for killing a man!&mdash;a good old law do you call that?</Q>&mdash;What a devil of a &s;pot have I got into here!&mdash;oh! what a picked place is little Ireland to this&mdash;we're poor enough to be &s;ure; but what of that? we can fight when we plea&s;e, can work when we plea&s;e, aye, and &s;tarve when we plea&s;e; and we can flouri&s;h our &s;helalahs, and &s;trut about our potatoe garden like a collection of Emperors.</P>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Adieu, dear Rachel! I mu&s;t go back to the &s;alt-mine.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rac.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah! Zarno, why do you remain in that mine? nay, don't be angry&mdash;you who lived in Cracow with the great Zorin&s;ki, were dre&s;&s;ed in furs and &s;ilk; and now, you wear the ba&s;e&s;t garments.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="22" REF="24">
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear Rachel! I have rea&s;ons, I cannot explain.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rac.</SPEAKER>
<P>What not to me, Zarno?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Should Zorin&s;ki know I have divulged&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rac.</SPEAKER>
<P>Zorin&s;ki!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ugh! <STAGE>(putting his hand to his mouth)</STAGE> Eh! &mdash;why &s;hould not I&mdash;ble&s;s her! does not &s;he de|&s;erve to be tru&s;ted?&mdash;Rachel! I'll tell thee a &s;e|cret, which, if known, would co&s;t Zarno his life.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rac.</SPEAKER>
<P>Would Zorin&s;ki kill thee?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>No; but I would kill my&s;elf for having betrayed him! Know then, in that dreary mine dwells, the great Zorin&s;ki&mdash;mark&mdash;when Ca&s;imir was crowned, Zorin&s;ki, who was all in all with the late King, could not bear the thwarts Ca&s;imir put on him; a quarrel en&s;ued, and my ma&s;ter, tho' I love him, was much to blame; di&s;grace followed. His hou&s;e, which had been the hive of courtiers, became de&s;erted&mdash;away they flew&mdash;his great &s;oul could not brook it! with de&s;pairing brow and knotted arms I &s;aw him leave the city; and &s;adly he walked along till he reached the opening of the mine.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rac.</SPEAKER>
<P>What to throw him&s;elf down head-long, and end his life?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>I dreaded it! &s;o fell at his feet: He took me by the hand; a big tear fell on it; he blu&s;hed, called me his faithful Zarno&mdash;bade me farewel!
<PB N="23" REF="25">
and gave me liberty&mdash;from that moment I be|came his &s;lave&mdash;we de&s;cended. into the mine, and I have attended him, and carried him his food&mdash;aye, and ever will. Ah, my dear ma&s;ter, never will Zarno leave thee! I &s;hared his pro&s;perity, and &s;hall I de&s;ert him now? no! no! Now Ra|chel thou ha&s;t the &s;ecret, and thus I &s;eal it up&mdash;farewel!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rac.</SPEAKER>
<P>But may not we hope for happier days, Zarno?</P>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>DUET&mdash;ZARNO and RACHEL.</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RACHEL.</SPEAKER>
<L>WHEN fir&s;t this little heart began</L>
<L>To feel an impul&s;e tender,</L>
<L>You &s;lily came, too faithle&s;s man,</L>
<L>And taught it to &s;urrender.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ZARNO.</SPEAKER>
<L>That dear reproach, which &s;eems to chide</L>
<L>The conque&s;t it confe&s;&s;es,</L>
<L>By words alone affects to hide</L>
<L>What every look expre&s;&s;es.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>BOTH.</SPEAKER>
<L>Then let us hope for the wedding day,</L>
<L>When we may merry make O,</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RACHEL.</SPEAKER>
<L>Care away&mdash;Zarno near,</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ZARNO.</SPEAKER>
<L>Lip to lip&mdash;Rachel dear.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="24" REF="26">
<SPEAKER>BOTH.</SPEAKER>
<L>And when to church we hie away,</L>
<L>Ding dong, ding dong, ding dong will go,</L>
<L>The merry bells at Cracow.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RACHEL.</SPEAKER>
<L>Sweet hours of love, but &s;hort as &s;weet,</L>
<L>For Rachel's bloom mu&s;t alter,</L>
<L>And Zarno other girls may meet,</L>
<L>And then his love may faulter.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ZARNO.</SPEAKER>
<L>My love will la&s;t while life endures,</L>
<L>Tho' Rachel look not younger,</L>
<L>For time, that lighter pa&s;&s;ions cures,</L>
<L>Will rivet mine the &s;tronger.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>BOTH.</SPEAKER>
<L>Then let us hope, &amp;c.</L>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER>END OF ACT I.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="act">
<PB N="25" REF="27">
<HEAD>ACT II.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE I.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">A SALT MINE.</HEAD>
<STAGE>ENTER <HI>down a &s;tair-ca&s;e</HI> RODOMSKO <HI>and</HI> NACLO.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rodom&s;ko.</SPEAKER>
<P>Begin your &s;earch. <STAGE>(exit Naclo)</STAGE> The place is awful&mdash;&s;ighs and groans, mixed with the madden|ing laugh of drunkards, pour along the&s;e ai&s;les a di&s;cord, that chills the very heart&mdash;how heavily mu&s;t woe have weighed him down, that makes this den his dwelling.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> NACLO.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nac.</SPEAKER>
<P>Look there my lord; behold him wiping from his brow, the painful drop of toil.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>He comes this way&mdash;what gloomy dignity&mdash;back&mdash;back. <STAGE>(they retire)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="26" REF="28"><HI>Enter</HI> ZORINSKI, <HI>with a &s;pade.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well toiled to day;&mdash;I often hope, that when the&s;e over-laboured limbs do pre&s;s their &s;traw, &s;weet &s;leep will give a &s;hort oblivion to my cares&mdash;but oh! then this big heart, forget|ful of its fall beats high, and wakes my brain to recollections, that go nigh to mad me&mdash;oh Zorin&s;ki&mdash;how, how long will this, thy body's hardihood &s;hake off the gripe of death&mdash;&s;hut from the &s;un, without a hope, without a friend,&mdash;nay that's not &s;o neither; Zarno, let me not wrong thee varlet&mdash;Zarno.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ZARNO.</STAGE>
<P>Come hither fellow&mdash;ha&s;t been on earth to day?</P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, my lord, and there's great news above.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Going my lord to Cracow, to buy pro|vi&s;ion, I pa&s;&s;ed the Diet, ju&s;t as the King&mdash; <STAGE>(Zorin&s;ki &s;tarts)</STAGE> my lord?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Go on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ju&s;t as the King came forth; and he looked &s;o kindly of us all&mdash;aye as if he'd been our father.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(much agitated)</STAGE>
<P>Father of all&mdash;and I alone rejected.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>And with him came the lord Radzano, whom every body &s;uppo&s;ed dead&mdash;he's to be the
<PB N="27" REF="29">
favourite now&mdash;and the palace your honour po&s;|&s;e&s;&s;ed, is to be &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(much agitated)</STAGE>
<P>Be dumb, have I not often told thee, villain, not to name&mdash;begone, <STAGE>(apart)</STAGE> What, proud heart mu&s;t thou &s;till play the tyrant&mdash;will not this dungeon humble thee&mdash;oh &s;hame&mdash;Come near me knave&mdash;I was to blame, Zarno.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>To blame, my lord, that you were not; you had a right to be angry, and if you had trod on me, you would have treated me as I de&s;erved: but will you, dear lord, forgive poor Zarno.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Forgive thee! <STAGE>(wiping his eyes)</STAGE> fond fool, 'tis ever thus he makes a woman of me&mdash;on with thy tale Zarno.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! that, that, that was all.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>What was all?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>That was all&mdash;about&mdash;about the&mdash; <STAGE>(hefi|ing)</STAGE> that is my lord&mdash;it's dinner time&mdash;I've had &s;uch an adventure.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>As how?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, trotting pa&s;t a kitchen hard by&mdash;I had ju&s;t been to &s;ee the King go&mdash; <STAGE>(&s;tops &s;uddenly)</STAGE> trotting pa&s;t a kitchen hard by, as hungry as a hunter, a curious &s;tew pre&s;ented it&s;elf&mdash;my no&s;e &s;tumbled at it, and I made as dead a &s;et as a dog at a partridge, and was ju&s;t going to &s;eize; when the che&s;nut faced cook, threw it all over me, and made that an out&s;ide covering, that I intended for an in|&s;ide lining.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="28" REF="30">
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! ha! come we'll in and laugh.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>It &s;melt &s;o &s;avoury&mdash;egad it was fit for a King, <STAGE>(&s;tops, hits his head)</STAGE> however, I have a mo&s;t delicious platter of pea&s;e and garlick.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I cannot feed. <STAGE>(&s;ighs)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not feed, my lord?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>No; in thou and eat.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, my lord&mdash;but you have taken away my appetite.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! &s;trangers&mdash;go in good fellow.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>I will, my lord&mdash;but could not you ju&s;t pick a bit?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Zorin&s;ki holds up his finger, Zarno exit bowing.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>If my eye err not&mdash;the lord Rodom&s;ko&mdash;&s;hould he know me! that's an idle fear; pro&s;perity hath but a &s;hallow memory, clothe its deare&s;t friend in rags, and on my life it puts him clean beyond his knowledge.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod. to Naclo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stand aloof. <STAGE>(approaches Zorin&s;ki)</STAGE> Your pardon, but when I behold &s;hut out from man, man's paragon&mdash;when in this loath&s;ome mine, I find a gem fit to illumine Poland, wonder not that I &s;hould wi&s;h to take it to my bo&s;om's intere&s;t; nor deem me, &s;ir, impelled by womani&s;h inqui&s;itivene&s;s, when I &s;eek to know the fortunes of a man, by fortune hardly dealt with.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>My &s;tory is but a dull monotony of &s;orrow&mdash;to repeat it, were but to &s;trike again the chord
<PB N="29" REF="31">
of dire calamity, and give a lengthened tone to melancholy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Are you of Poland?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, of the eque&s;trian order.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Gentleman of Poland&mdash;that envied dig|nity's a ble&s;&s;ing&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>It has been my cur&s;e&mdash;born to command&mdash;my &s;tubborn nature will not bow to my condi|tion&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<Q><SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sure no crime has &s;tained&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, the mo&s;t mon&s;trous&mdash;poverty&mdash;that fiend accur&s;ed&mdash;the &s;lave whom he en|counters pro&s;trates in the du&s;t, and by humi|lity e&s;capes his fangs&mdash;but meeting with a rough, imperious &s;pirit, pride, and he around him, twine their venomed knots, and hold the victim &s;ure&mdash;for know, lord, though penury and &s;orrow be the &s;ad inmates of this bo&s;om, my &s;oul di&s;dains the cur&s;e of benefits&mdash;rather than &s;o&mdash;I dungeon here, litter with devils, and out-toil the hind.</P>
</SP></Q>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>&mdash;Brother, are our rights dear to thee?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>By the &s;acred plain of Vola&mdash;dearer than &s;ight, for that &s;hews me but a hated world&mdash;dear as to the damned the joys of heaven&mdash;for I, like them, langui&s;h for ble&s;&s;ings which I ne'er mu&s;t ta&s;te&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<Q><SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not &s;o&mdash;for I will put thee on a pur|po&s;e, that &s;hall mount thy fortunes till they
<PB N="30" REF="32">
reach the noble elevation of thy &s;oul&mdash;make thee&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray be careful&mdash;&s;o long I've bani&s;hed hope from this &s;ad brea&s;t, that its incur&s;ion now is aching to the &s;en&s;e&mdash;drag not, at once, the dungeon'd wretch before the orb of day, and blind him with his ble&s;sings. Oh, Sir, &s;o long misfortune's bla&s;ts have riven this rugged trunk&mdash;&s;o long has mi&s;ery &s;apped my roots, and torn away each fibre that &s;u&s;tained me, that the fun of hope (that greate&s;t good) warms but to wither&mdash;&s;hines but to de&s;troy me&mdash;</P>
</SP></Q>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come cheerly, cheerly&mdash;in the chequered play of fortune, the be&s;t regarded mu&s;t expect mi&s;chance&mdash;&s;ees't thou the &s;leeky knaves of the court&mdash;be wi&s;e&mdash;ma&s;k thy heart, and learn to flatter&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Flatter!&mdash;I tell thee, lord, as ea&s;y were it for our &s;tern Carpathian mountains, to &s;hake from their rugged brows, their everla&s;ting &s;nows, as for this tongue to bring forth what this heart doth not beget&mdash;flatter!&mdash;'&s;death&mdash;join gripe with what I hate!&mdash;&s;train to my heart its fixed anti|pathy!&mdash;by Almighty truth, I &s;wear, the poi&s;oned twine of adders round this brea&s;t were grateful to't&mdash;thou know'&s;t me not&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nor can &s;carce believe&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yet, Rodom&s;ko&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! my name!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="31" REF="33">
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, lord!&mdash;yet, I &s;ay, thou wilt believe, when I tell thee that this abject, rugged, heart|broken wretch was once Zorin&s;ki&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Zorin&s;ki here!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>What could I do?&mdash;live with men to bla&s;t me with their pity?&mdash;no; when di&s;grace pur&s;ued, I earthed me here, le&s;t, Acteon like, I &s;hould be hunted by that yelping pack of courtly knaves, my bounty had given breath to.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Zorin&s;ki, again to fold thee, and at an hour of &s;uch dread moment.&mdash;Oft have I, in the &s;enate, mourned thy lo&s;s&mdash;but in&s;tant leave this den&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>To the world again?&mdash;What &s;hould I there&mdash;but ca&s;t a mournful look around, and, on the wide &s;urface of nature, &s;ee nothing I could claim, except a grave.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Away with this&mdash;by manhood, 'tis baby weakne&s;s.&mdash;Oh, Zorin&s;ki, there are purpo&s;es&mdash; <STAGE>(the noi&s;e of a bugle horn is heard above)</STAGE>&mdash;Ca&s;imir hawks to day.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye&mdash;Again he treads upon me. <STAGE>(looking up.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>He does&mdash;thy fall Zorin&s;ki&mdash;nay, droop not, man, at what &s;hould fire thee&mdash;thy fall &s;hall be revenged&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes; rouze thee, for vengeance is at hand. The confederated lords, allied in wrongs,
<PB N="32" REF="34">
are ripe for action; and, let but thy a&s;piring &s;oul re&s;ume its energy&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, thou ha&s;t poured again into this brea&s;t ambition's godlike impul&s;e. Tell me, Rodom&s;ko, can the devotion of this life, this &s;oul, forward the illu&s;trious cau&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mo&s;t mightily, for the fate of Poland hangs upon thy breath.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Shall I to the &s;enate&mdash;there&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Twere u&s;ele&s;s all. Did rea&s;on u&s;e Jove's thunder, 'twould be outroared by the clamorous people, who pay this Ca&s;imir a wor&s;hip, e'en to the wronging of high heaven. Oh, my friend, action is vengeance's language&mdash;thy arm Zo|rin&s;ki&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have for thy ear words of deep per&s;ua|&s;ion and mightie&s;t import&mdash;but the time's un|fitting&mdash;in&s;tant leave this hated place.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Foul den I quit thee, and with thee im|potent de&s;pondency&mdash;lead&mdash;yet hold&mdash;I've here a faithful &s;lave that mu&s;t not be forgotten&mdash;Zarno&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ZARNO.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Prepare to leave this place.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>My lord&mdash;eh&mdash;what&mdash;leave this place&mdash;Oh dear&mdash;ha, hah&mdash;I'm &s;o glad of it&mdash;an't you, Sir? <STAGE>(to Rodom&s;ko, who frowns.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="33" REF="35">
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Peace, familiar fool.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>There. <STAGE>(throws him a pur&s;e.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>There; <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE> cur&s;e his money&mdash;a churl|i&s;h&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thoul't follow, Zarno.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh to be &s;ure I will. I'll only take leave of my fellow devils, and mount in a twinkling. Oh, I'm &s;o happy&mdash;hollo, hollo!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Rodom&s;ko and Zorin&s;ki exeunt up the &s;tair-ca&s;e.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> MINERS.</STAGE>
<P>Ah! you mi&s;erable, jolly dogs, how are you? In &s;ooth this digging in a &s;alt-mine is very pro|ductive, for, while many an hone&s;t gentleman above can't get &s;alt to his porridge, you may &s;wal|low it by &s;hovels full&mdash;farewel to you all.</P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Miner.</SPEAKER>
<P>Are you going to leave us, Zarno?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes; for though this is certainly a very delectable &s;ituation, yet I find, by con&s;ulting my gla&s;s, it rather annoys the complexion; and, my phy&s;icians &s;ay, that this air induces &s;pleen and melancholy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Miner.</SPEAKER>
<P>He's mad!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mad, am I? Then there, <STAGE>(gives money)</STAGE> there's what will make you all drunk, and then you will be as mad as I am. There goes the old carle's money&mdash;drink, devils, drink.</P>
</SP>
<Q><PB N="34" REF="36">
<TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>SONG&mdash;</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ZARNO.</SPEAKER>
<LG>
<L>GOOD bye my fellow devils dear,</L>
<L>Fal, lal, lal, &amp;c.</L>
<L>Long time I have been pickling here,</L>
<L>Adieu! adieu! adieu!</L>
<L>O weep not, friends, becau&s;e I go,</L>
<L>Re&s;train your briny drops of woe;</L>
<L>Unmanly weeping is a fault,</L>
<L>And tears, like your's, are wond'rous &s;alt.</L>
<L>Fal, lal, lal, &amp;c.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2">
<HEAD>II.</HEAD>
<L>The mine has made me pale and wan,</L>
<L>Fal, lal, lal, &amp;c.</L>
<L>Salt cures a hog, but kills a man,</L>
<L>Adieu! adieu! adieu!</L>
<L>I hope your liquor may be found</L>
<L>Not very dead, though under ground:</L>
<L>So re&s;t ye merry, while I go,</L>
<L>And thus I quit the &s;hades below.</L>
<L>Fal, lal, lal, &amp;c.</L>
</LG>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<STAGE>Exeunt</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE II.&mdash;<HI>A View on</HI> RADZANO'S <HI>E&s;tate.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> WITSKI, <HI>followed by</HI> WINIFRED.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, my dear wife, my dear Winifred, now do &s;top that tongue of thine&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Win.</SPEAKER>
<P>I won't hold my tongue, and, what's more, I'll tell Mr. Amalekite how you u&s;e me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="35" REF="37">
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, there it is&mdash;Oh, what a hard lot is mine&mdash;if I don't &s;ubmit to her in every thing, then &s;he threatens to encourage that old, amorous Jew&mdash;now pray be quiet.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Win.</SPEAKER>
<P>I won't be quiet&mdash;I will have my own way&mdash;and I won't be &s;nubbed&mdash;and I will be heard&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> O'CURRAGH.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>What's all this chatter about?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>Winny, Winny, Winny, don't provoke me; you ought to know by this time I am a man.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Win.</SPEAKER>
<P>And you ought to know by this time I am a woman.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, zounds! why &s;o loud? Do you want all the world to know you are a woman?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>No quarreling to day. Come, you cooing turtle&mdash;did ever magpie keep up &s;o damned a chatter!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Win.</SPEAKER>
<P>I won't hold my tongue. Oh, here comes Mr. Amalekite&mdash;obey me, or you know what&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, I do know what&mdash; <STAGE>(rubbing his fore|head)</STAGE> and yet I won't &s;ubmit&mdash;if heaven has willed it&mdash;why&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Win.</SPEAKER>
<P>Heaven's will be done, I &s;ay.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>An't you &s;urpri&s;ed, friend?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>Faith, not much at the thing, but a good deal at her choice&mdash;for if horns be the
<PB N="36" REF="38">
word, its allowed, I believe, that no one makes a bull more neatly than an Iri&s;hman.</P>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>DUET&mdash;WINIFRED and WITSKI.</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINIFRED.</SPEAKER>
<L>A Piper o'er the meadows &s;traying,</L>
<L>Met a &s;imple maid a maying,</L>
<L>Straight he won her heart by playing;</L>
<L>Fal de ral, &amp;c.</L>
<L>Wedded, &s;oon each tone grew teazing,</L>
<L>Fal de ral, &amp;c.</L>
<L>His Pipe had lo&s;t the power of plea&s;ing,</L>
<L>Fal de ral, &amp;c.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WITSKI.</SPEAKER>
<L>Wedlock's laws are hard and griping,</L>
<L>Women fretful&mdash;arts are ripe in,</L>
<L>'Twas his wife that &s;poil'd his piping,</L>
<L>Fal de ral, &amp;c.</L>
<L>Her &s;hrill note marr'd every &s;onnet,</L>
<L>Fal de ral, &amp;c.</L>
<L>And crack'd his pipe, depend upon it,</L>
<L>Fal de ral, &amp;c.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINIFRED.</SPEAKER>
<L>Silly wives too late di&s;cover,</L>
<L>When the honey-moon is over,</L>
<L>Har&s;h grows very piping lover,</L>
<L>Fal de ral, &amp;c.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WITSKI.</SPEAKER>
<L>Zounds why teaze, morn, night, and noon now,</L>
<L>With fal de ral, &amp;c.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="37" REF="39">
<SPEAKER>WINIFRED.</SPEAKER>
<L>Your pipe, my dear, is out of tune now.</L>
<L>Fal de ral, &amp;c.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>BOTH.</SPEAKER>
<L>Why then teaze, morn, night, and noon now?</L>
<L>Fal de ral, &amp;c.</L>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> AMALEKITE, <HI>and Slaves.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ama.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fall back there&mdash;fall back&mdash;ah, go&s;&s;ip Winifred. <STAGE>(takes her hand)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh dear, oh lord&mdash;what &s;hall I do&mdash;I can't bear it&mdash;I &s;ay Winny, Winny&mdash;I yield&mdash;&s;ubmit&mdash;any thing, <STAGE>(pulling her away by the gown)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>Was there ever &s;uch a hen-pecked fool? But, I &s;ay, <STAGE>(to Amalekite)</STAGE> have you told the pea&s;ants that they are now become the &s;laves of my lord Radzano?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ama.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have. But pray, why be they a&s;&s;embled now?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>Becau&s;e my ma&s;ter is coming hither with his &s;weet bride, that is to be, to receive their homage.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> RACHEL.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rac.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, dear father, Zarno has left the &s;alt-mine,
<PB N="38" REF="40">
and, he &s;ays, he'll &s;oon be rich, and then he'll buy me of that old rogue Amalekite.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ama.</SPEAKER>
<P>Vill he &s;o, &s;lut&mdash;de old rogue will pre|vent him though.&mdash;Old rogue&mdash;you and your fader &s;hall &s;mart for dat.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stand back; here comes my lord and his &s;weet, &s;weet bride; now mind your hits all of you. I &s;ay, have you the roll with the &s;laves names?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ama.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes; here it is.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> RADZANO <HI>and</HI> ROSOLIA, <HI>attended.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rad.</SPEAKER>
<P>Surely &s;weet, tho&s;e who&s;e loves run in unruffled &s;moothne&s;s, and never feel calamity's chill bla&s;t, cannot ta&s;te my joy. Oh lovely, con|&s;tant maiden, ne'er was Radzano proud till now.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ro&s;o.</SPEAKER>
<P>Con&s;tant! be&s;tow not prai&s;e on that which not to be, were to be nought. If con&s;tancy be worthy prai&s;e, be it thine Radzano, for thou ha&s;t &s;ojourned e'en in beauty's court, and yet&mdash;forgot not thy Ro&s;olia. Look, dear lord, your va&s;&s;als are a&s;&s;embled; ah! they little know the ble&s;&s;ings that await them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rad.</SPEAKER>
<P>Amalekite, give me the roll, and bid the &s;laves approach.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ama. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Pre&s;enting the roll)</STAGE>
<P>I am much afraid he mean to favour dem; I no like his looks&mdash;oh, he has a damned benevolent countenance. <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ro&s;o.</SPEAKER>
<P>Poor wretches! how they tremble.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="39" REF="41">
<SPEAKER>Rad.</SPEAKER>
<P>Approach, and fear not; in this you and your children are regi&s;tered my &s;laves, and live but in my will; acknowledge ye your va&s;&s;alage? <STAGE>(the &s;laves pro&s;trate tbem&s;elves)</STAGE> Ri&s;e, then, and mark: By this you are recorded &s;laves, but by this <STAGE>(tearing the roll)</STAGE> you are no longer &s;laves, but men. <STAGE>(The mo&s;t extravagant &s;igns of joy are di&s;played)</STAGE> The world's before you&mdash;who will remain with me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pea&s;ants.</SPEAKER>
<P>All, all.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rad.</SPEAKER>
<P>The brighte&s;t page of nature's bounteous charter is freedom to her children; that I po&s;&s;e&s;s you of; but, oh, contemn not ju&s;t re&s;traint, else 'twill prove a cur&s;e more galling than the mo&s;t abject &s;lavery tyranny e'er compa&s;&s;ed; &s;ee, there|fore, you abu&s;e it not.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ro&s;o.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, impo&s;&s;ible; while e'en the &s;pade they toiled with was their lord's, vice and &s;loth po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ed them, for what incitement had they to indu&s;try? but when they find their labour will cheer their children, and throw content around their humble cots&mdash;ah, dear lord, the&s;e ble&s;&s;ings &s;trike too &s;weetly on the heart to fear abu&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rad.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fair advocate, &s;ee their hearts thank thee. Come hither, fellow; <STAGE>(to Wit&s;ki)</STAGE> fear not, man; give me thy hand; for the love I know thou bear'&s;t me, remember this&mdash;the mill thou long ha&s;t toiled in, is thine own.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="40" REF="42">
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh dear! oh dear! I &s;hall run mad with joy&mdash;I know I &s;hall&mdash;my mill!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ama.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(A&s;ide)</STAGE>
<P>Oh, de devil&mdash;it is all over vid me.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> MESSENGER, <HI>who gives a paper to</HI> RADZANO.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Me&s;&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>From the King.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rad.</SPEAKER>
<P>The royal mandate calls me to council; the King doth here entreat thy pardon, for thus anticipating widowhood, and bids thee, &s;weet, pre|pare thy lute, that jocundly this night may pa&s;s in mirth and min&s;trel&s;y; till night, then, farewel dear mi&s;tre&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ro&s;o.</SPEAKER>
<P>Heaven &s;peed your councils; my lowly duty to the King.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rad.</SPEAKER>
<P>Guards, attend. <STAGE>Exit Ro&s;olia atteded.</STAGE></P>
<P>O'Curragh, my faithful fellow, ob&s;erve Rodom&s;ko, if you &s;hould &s;u&s;pect him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, I don't &s;u&s;pect him at all&mdash;I know he's a rogue.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rad.</SPEAKER>
<P>Should his conduct threaten danger, on the in&s;tant hie thee to Cracow&mdash;remember&mdash;freemen farewel. <STAGE>Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yonder he goes&mdash;now he's at the top of the hill&mdash;&s;ee, he waves his hand to us&mdash;heaven ble&s;s him!&mdash;heaven ble&s;s him!&mdash;freemen, fare|wel&mdash;Oh my head, my head&mdash;I'm &s;ure I &s;hall go mad&mdash;I feel I &s;hall&mdash;I'll run home and tell
<PB N="41" REF="43">
the cow and the mill&mdash;<HI>my</HI> mill&mdash;only think of that&mdash; <STAGE>(walks backwards and forwards, and each time jo&s;tles Amalekite, without noticing him)</STAGE>&mdash;damme, I am a man, a freeman, and a gentleman! <STAGE>(to O'Cur.)</STAGE> Sir, I &s;hall be proud to &s;ee you at my man&s;ion!&mdash;<HI>my</HI> man&s;ion.&mdash;That's right, is not it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure; you are lord of it, and may knock any man's brains out that comes in without your leave.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>May I though&mdash;ecod, that's jolly&mdash;he! he! he! Then I'll tell you what, <STAGE>(to Amalekite)</STAGE> if ever I catch that black muzzle within the por|tico of my mill, I'll grind you into &s;au&s;ages, I will, you ugly dog. Wi&s;e! now we'll &s;ee who's man of the hou&s;e&mdash;wife!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Win.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh my dear Witski.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>Silence, &s;ilence! there. <STAGE>(gives her his hand to ki&s;s)</STAGE> that's right is not it? he! he! he!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Win.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'm dumb, but don't be angry.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>Angry; I could not be angry if I would&mdash;he! he! come bu&s;s me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ama.</SPEAKER>
<P>Go&s;&s;ip Winifred?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Win.</SPEAKER>
<P>Keep off man, I only encouraged you as a &s;carecrow to frighten my hu&s;band&mdash;but now&mdash;faugh!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well &s;aid Winny! ah Rachel my girl, ki&s;s thy honoured parent.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rac.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh father, won't you let me marry Zarno?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="42" REF="44">
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, to-morrow morning, with all my heart and &s;oul.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rac.</SPEAKER>
<P>And here he comes.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ZARNO.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Joy, joy, joy to you all&mdash;I've heard the news&mdash;ah dear Rachel, <STAGE>(pu&s;hing a&s;ide Amalekite)</STAGE> I'm &s;o happy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rac.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;o fine!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ecod, that he is.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Am I think you? yes pretty well&mdash;&s;word and cap, and altogether! eh, yes it's not &s;hewy but neat, it's becoming&mdash;now my jolly dad, that is to be. <STAGE>(walks about jo&s;tling Amalekite)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>How do yo do Mr. Amalekite, you don't &s;eem to comprehend what's going forward here&mdash;will you try your hand at that, <STAGE>(gives a paper)</STAGE> there's your quietus for you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ama. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(drops the paper)</STAGE>
<P>My di&s;charge! ble&s;s my con&s;cience! <STAGE>(is going out de&s;pondingly)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>You move rather &s;low&mdash;come, for old ac|quaintance &s;ake, I'll give you a lift, <STAGE>(pu&s;hes him off)</STAGE> ju&s;t &s;et him agoing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! it was time to put a &s;top to &s;uch a rogue! now I'm to be &s;teward&mdash;which is an office&mdash;an office&mdash;oh! fir&s;t I am to take particular care, to receive the rents of &s;uch tenants as won't pay&mdash;and &s;econdly, to &s;ee that no one behaves im|properly,
<PB N="43" REF="45">
without my over-looking him&mdash;yes that's it&mdash;now I mu&s;t away to the ca&s;tle.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh there are to be great doings there&mdash;the King is to be there&mdash;and Rachel you &s;hall be there&mdash;I'll meet thee to night in the wood, the old place&mdash;and then to-morrow when the friar comes&mdash;oh you blu&s;hing tempting rogue.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now, brother freemen, to our homes&mdash;drink pro&s;perity to our deliverer, and be merry and happy all the re&s;t of our lives.</P>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>SONG AND CHORUS.</HEAD>
<STAGE>WITSKI, WINIFRED, ZARNO, RACHEL, and O'CURRAGH.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WITSKI.</SPEAKER>
<L>No longer a ninny,</L>
<L>But Lord of my mill,</L>
<L>With my jug and my Winny,</L>
<L>Full jorums I'll &s;will.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINIFRED.</SPEAKER>
<L>Ever con&s;tant and humble,</L>
<L>Your Winifred &s;hall prove,</L>
<L>And, without e'en a grumble,</L>
<L>Obediently love.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHORUS.</SPEAKER>
<L>La, la, la, &amp;c.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="44" REF="46">
<SPEAKER>RACHEL.</SPEAKER>
<L>In a &s;alt mine &s;o drearily,</L>
<L>Of the dumps you'd your &s;wing,</L>
<L>But now bri&s;k and cheerily,</L>
<L>With Rachel you &s;ing.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ZARNO.</SPEAKER>
<L>Let the tabor go bing bang,</L>
<L>The pipe &s;hrilly play,</L>
<L>The &s;weet guitar go ting tang,</L>
<L>On Zarno's wedding day.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHORUS.</SPEAKER>
<L>La, la, la, &amp;c.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'CURRAGH.</SPEAKER>
<L>Then dance, &s;ing, and caper,</L>
<L>Ye merry men &s;o gay,</L>
<L>And while bri&s;kly plays the &s;craper,</L>
<L>For liberty huzza!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHORUS.</SPEAKER>
<L>Then dance, &s;ing, and caper,</L>
<L>Ye merry men &s;o gay, &amp;c.</L>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<STAGE>Exeunt.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE III.&mdash;<HI>An Apartment in</HI> RODOMSKO'S <HI>Ca&s;tle.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE>Enter RODOMSKO <HI>and</HI> NACLO.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>I tell thee, fellow, Zorin&s;ki will be won&mdash;where are thy comrades?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="45" REF="47">
<SPEAKER>Nac.</SPEAKER>
<P>Shrouded in the neighbouring fore&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Bring them hither&mdash;but &s;ee they hold no conver&s;e with my people&mdash;be firm good Naclo, for my confidence re&s;ts weightily upon thee.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit Naclo.</STAGE>
<P>Within there!</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> SERVANT.</STAGE>
<P>Bid anon my daughter touch her lute&mdash; <STAGE>[Exit. Servant]</STAGE> for now the bloody purpo&s;e being un|folded, all traps mu&s;t be &s;et for him&mdash;Ha! he approaches, and in heavy rumination.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ZORINSKI.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tho' Ca&s;imir has &s;orely urged me to revenge, by the mo&s;t galling wrongs, yet to murder&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(taking his hand)</STAGE>
<P>Was Brutus then a murderer&mdash;genius of Poland where &s;leepe&s;t thou, when thy patricians &s;hrink from achieving, what tho&s;e of Rome contended for.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Grant he ought to die&mdash;yet&mdash;&s;oft, <STAGE>(a lute is heard behind, which plays &s;ome time)</STAGE> what heavenly &s;ounds? much I thank thee unknown min&s;trel; for thy enchantment has pri&s;ohed down the hell-born pa&s;&s;ions that po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ed me, and &s;oothed my &s;oul to tranquil melancholy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Twas my daughter's lute: within there&mdash;Ro&s;olia! &s;ee, &s;he approaches.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="46" REF="48">
<SPEAKER>Zo. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(&s;tarts)</STAGE>
<P>What magic &s;weetne&s;s&mdash;do not wonder at me, for &s;o long the&s;e eyes have been unu&s;ed to look on beauty, that its inroad now riots my pul&s;e, e'en perhaps to boyi&s;h folly&mdash;let me avoid its witchery, <STAGE>(going)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hold!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ROSOLIA.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ro&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>What wills my father?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Where ha&s;t been my girl?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ro&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Enjoying the riche&s;t luxury of greatne&s;s&mdash; &s;eeing the poor made happy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, by whom?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ro&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>E'en my intended lord&mdash; <STAGE>(Zorin&s;ki &s;tarts)</STAGE> this day he hath given freedom to his va&s;&s;als, and much I joyed to behold wretched man re&s;cued from abject &s;lavery.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lovelie&s;t maiden, thy tender nature ne'er can impo&s;e chains, &s;ave tho&s;e of love's &s;oft thraldrom.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>By heaven he's caught&mdash;Ro&s;olia, I here pre&s;ent thy father's deare&s;t friend.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ro&s;</SPEAKER>
<P>Deign, Sir, to receive my hearty greeting.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(&s;alutes her)</STAGE>
<P>The fa&s;cinating poi&s;on thrills my every nerve&mdash;all powerful love&mdash;love&mdash;ar't mad Zorin&s;ki&mdash;thou who &s;corn'&s;t to flatter others&mdash;be to thy&s;elf con&s;i&s;tent&mdash;<Q>is this rugged frame &s;haped for love's &s;oft dalliance&mdash;do amorous
<PB N="47" REF="49">
whi&s;pers &s;oft as the zephyr, come from a voice chill and &s;urly as the northern bla&s;t</Q>&mdash;is this &s;cowling eye, now rife with murder, a place for Cu|pids to ambu&s;h in&mdash;mockery all&mdash;yet, on my &s;oul, I dare not tru&s;t my eyes to look upon her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ro&s;o.</SPEAKER>
<P>He &s;eems much moved.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thou ha&s;t done well my girl&mdash;bid him farewell, and get thee in.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ro&s;o.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tho' ignorant in what; I am right glad I've plea&s;ed you father&mdash;courteous Sir!&mdash;&s;weet peace be with you. <STAGE>Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>That will never be again&mdash; <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE> talked &s;he not of marriage?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye with the young lord Radzano&mdash;'tis a match of the King's making.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(with &s;urly irritation)</STAGE>
<P>Ca&s;imir, do'&s;t thou again thwart me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>E'en now the King is journeying hither with his young friend, to con&s;ummate the union.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Happy Radzano&mdash;wedded, and to-mor|row?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, but, &s;hould a real friend to Poland think her worthy&mdash;never.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh Zorin&s;ki! act but to night as doth be|come thee&mdash;vindicate thy owa wrongs, avenge the Lords of Poland, and&mdash;receive my daughter to thy arms; for by her blu&s;hing beauties I &s;wear &s;he's thine.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="48" REF="50">
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh Rodom&s;ko! tempt me not beyond man's bearing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dull man, I tempt thee to a throne&mdash;Ca&s;imir being di&s;po&s;ed of&mdash;his place mu&s;t be &s;upplied; and whom will thy peers deem &s;o fit to guard their rights, as he who cru&s;hed their fell de&s;troyer.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>If thou wilt place before me temptations more than mortal, he mu&s;t be more than mortal that re&s;i&s;ts&mdash;by hell I'm thine&mdash;Ca&s;imir or Zo|rin&s;ki falls&mdash;&s;o may my &s;oul find life or death eternal.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>But this night.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>The better.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>And mark; &s;hould chance &s;o order it; bring Ca&s;imir alive&mdash;the confederate lords de|mand him for their vengeance&mdash;a band, who&s;e &s;teely hearts are rivetted with oaths, will aid thee.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I need them not&mdash;let daws cling together&mdash;the eagle flies alone.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Away with this romantic folly&mdash;within there is prepared a &s;olemn &s;acrament, think on't.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>If thou would'&s;t have me act this deed; oh let me <HI>not</HI> think, Rodom&s;ko&mdash;but on the in&s;tant give me the deadly oath&mdash;aye, 'tis well con|ceived&mdash;'twill &s;ave revolt and cowardly com|punction&mdash;for oh the dread interval will be a helli&s;h purgatory, but it leads to a heaven of
<PB N="49" REF="51">
bli&s;s&mdash;&s;o love and proud ambition receive your votary. <STAGE>Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>My &s;oul is &s;atisfied.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>O'CURRAGH <HI>enters behind, &s;eeing</HI> RODOMSKO, <HI>retire.</HI></STAGE>
<P>Now bu&s;tle all&mdash;Ro&s;olia&mdash;my daughter&mdash;&s;tir wench.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ROSOLIA.</STAGE>
<P>Prepare to leave the ca&s;tle in&s;tantly.</P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ro&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>My father!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Que&s;tion not why nor where.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ro&s;o.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Be dumb&mdash;within there.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> SERVANT.</STAGE>
<P>Arm fifty cho&s;en va&s;&s;als&mdash;and to the &s;outhern inlett of the fore&s;t &s;peed with my hor&s;es&mdash;away.</P>
<STAGE>Exit Servant.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ro&s;o. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(kneels)</STAGE>
<P>Oh my father! if humanity dwell in you, ea&s;e this heart&mdash;kill not your daughter's happine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thy happine&s;s, weak girl; Zorin&s;ki will take good care of that.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ro&s;o.</SPEAKER>
<P>Zorin&s;ki!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>I tell thee, the fate of Poland is in &s;u&s;|pen&s;e&mdash;along I &s;ay.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="50" REF="52">
<SPEAKER>Ro&s;o.</SPEAKER>
<P>Rather take my life.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>It will not &s;erve my turn&mdash;No &s;trug|gling&mdash;your chamber, your chamber.</P>
<STAGE>Exeunt.</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE>O'CURRAGH <HI>comes forward.</HI></STAGE>
<P>Oh, oh! there bids fair to be foul play here. Oh, the confu&s;ion of all Ireland upon that Ro|dom&s;ko, I &s;ay. What the devil &s;hall I do? If I go to my lord at Cracow, I can't very con|veniently &s;tay here to &s;ee what will become of his lady&mdash;Oh, if this head would but prevent a mi&s;take by blundering on what's right&mdash;I have it&mdash;I'll follow her, and if lo&s;ing my life will enable me to take her away with me, I'll do it with all the plea&s;ure in nature. Oh, to die for &s;uch a lady, and &s;uch a ma&s;ter, is what no faithful &s;ervant would ever repent of. <STAGE>Exit.</STAGE></P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> RODOMSKO <HI>and</HI> NACLO.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now, good Naclo, &s;pirit up thy com|rades. Are they at hand? <STAGE>(Naclo beckons)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter A&s;&s;a&s;&s;ins.</STAGE>
<P>Ye &s;pirits of noble daring, this night acquit your&s;elves, and you are made for ever; there's to cheer you. <STAGE>(throws money)</STAGE> Naclo, your
<PB N="51" REF="53">
leader will anon meet you&mdash;be firm, good Naclo. <STAGE>Exit.</STAGE></P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Naclo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now, gentlemen, &s;et hands and hearts to the bu&s;ine&s;s&mdash;night is coming on apace, and then&mdash; <STAGE>(laying his hand on his &s;word)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t A&s;&s;a&s;&s;in.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fear us not, comrade.</P>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHORUS OF ASSASSINS.</SPEAKER>
<L>While the hideous night is &s;cowling,</L>
<L>While the &s;avage bear is growling,</L>
<L>Thro' the di&s;mal fore&s;ts prowling,</L>
<L>Fir&s;t with &s;tealing &s;tep, and hu&s;h,</L>
<L>Then, like a torrent, on we ru&s;h,</L>
<L>And immolate our foe.</L>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<STAGE>Exeunt.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER>END OF ACT II.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="act">
<PB N="52" REF="54">
<HEAD>ACT III.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE I.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">A WOOD.&mdash;NIGHT.</HEAD>
<STAGE>ENTER O'CURRAGH.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Curragh.</SPEAKER>
<P>OH! I'm &s;ure mi&s;chief is going forward, every thing is &s;o peaceable, and torches keep fla&s;hing about like a battalion of jack-lanterns&mdash;one good thing is, that the old rogue, Rodom&s;ko, has lo&s;t his way and his attendants; there was &s;uch a train of them, that I found the be&s;t mode of pur&s;uing was getting before them. Oh! he hauls my &s;weet lady along there, as if &s;he were his wife in&s;tead of his daughter&mdash;now's your time O'Curragh! Oh, Saint Patrick! I'll ju&s;t beg leave to trouble you for five minutes, <STAGE>(retires)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ROSOLIA, <HI>leaning on Rodom&s;ko.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ro&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed, I can no further.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, good Ro&s;olia! come&mdash;wayward
<PB N="53" REF="55">
and &s;tubborn; on, I &s;ay&mdash;tho&s;e vile erring &s;laves, not to return, my cur&s;es on them! entangled in this labyrinth, each &s;tep bewilders more&mdash;ha! their torches gleam thro' yonder valley&mdash; <STAGE>(During this, O'Curragh attracts the attention of Ro&s;olia)</STAGE> who's there?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ro&s;. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(with apprehen&s;ion)</STAGE>
<P>'Tis your faithful &s;lave, Kali&s;h.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rod.</SPEAKER>
<P>Right glad am I of that&mdash; <STAGE>(&s;till looking after his va&s;&s;als)</STAGE>&mdash;death and hell they take their cour&s;e athwart! good Kali&s;h tarry with Ro&s;olia&mdash;&s;tir not be &s;ure&mdash;but I know thy hone&s;ty. <STAGE>Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>For once, old gentleman, you have &s;poken truth by mi&s;take.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ro&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! &s;ave me, good fellow.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>This way, &s;weete&s;t lady!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ro&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! Radzano, where art thou? perhaps e'en now the victim of foul con&s;piracy; where will my &s;orrows end!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, put your tru&s;t in St. Patrick, out and out the genteele&s;t &s;aint in the calendar. <STAGE>Exeunt.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="scene">
<PB N="54" REF="56">
<HEAD>SCENE II.&mdash;<HI>Another part of the Fore&s;t.</HI></HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub"><HI>Scene draws and di&s;covers</HI> ZORINSKI <HI>with his Sabre in his hand, leaning de&s;pondingly again&s;t the Arm of a Tree.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ZARNO.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>What can make Rachel tarry &s;o? it's an infernal night! it rains, blows, thunders, and whew!&mdash;this is weather to try a lover in&mdash;Where can Rachel be&mdash;<HI>(&s;ees Zorin&s;ki)</HI> What&mdash;eh! my ma&s;ter here and his &s;abre in his hand&mdash;my mind mi&s;gives me! Oh! &s;ome villainy of that rogue, Rodom&s;ko. <STAGE>(&s;eeing Zorin&s;ki come for|ward, retires.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! Zorin&s;ki, how art thou fallen?&mdash;confederate with hired a&s;&s;a&s;&s;ins&mdash;fettered by deadly oaths&mdash;how changed the face of all things?&mdash;the heavens &s;eem grimed with pitch as back as Acheron, and the ru&s;tling wind &s;trikes on my ear e'en as the hi&s;&s;ing of hell's &s;erpents. <STAGE>(Zarno approaches, Zorin&s;ki &s;tarts)</STAGE> Oh, all the devils! do I tremble?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Lord!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Zarno, thou did'&s;t not &s;ay I trembled.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Lord! your are pale, and your voice faulters&mdash;I fear you are very ill.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, that's it, that's it, good Zarno&mdash;my pul&s;e is fevered, and that effects the brain&mdash; <STAGE><HI>(with
<PB N="55" REF="57">&s;olemnity)</HI></STAGE> a little blood &s;pilt, and all will be well&mdash;Leave me, Zarno.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, Zarno, leave you when you are ill? oh! no. Ah, ma&s;ter! don't you remember in the mine when an ague &s;hook you, how Zarno watched you, and when I blubbered over you&mdash;you wept too.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, there was a time when I could weep. Zarno, I charge thee leave this place!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! dear Lord&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(hearing a noi&s;e)</STAGE>
<P>Hu&s;h! not a breath.</P>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Some horrid purpo&s;e po&s;&s;e&s;&s;es him&mdash;now he &s;tops.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ROSOLIA <HI>and</HI> O'CURRAGH.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who's there?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ro&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, &s;tranger! aid an unhappy maiden, who, torn from her &s;oul's only hope, and well nigh dead with wearine&s;s, humbly implores thy &s;uc|cour, to unwind the mazes of this wood, and lead her on her way to Cracow. <STAGE>(Zarno &s;till looks after his ma&s;ter)</STAGE> Radzano will reward thee.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(turns round)</STAGE>
<P>Good heavens! the lady Ro&s;olia, and here&mdash;dear lady, I'll go with you to the world's end&mdash;only I've a little bu&s;ine&s;s here, that&mdash; <STAGE>(returns to his ob&s;ervation)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ro&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come then, good fellow!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="56" REF="58">
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes; I'm coming. <STAGE>(moving from her)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hark you; that may be coming; but it looks &s;o like going, that you will plea&s;e to move this way.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Unhand me, or&mdash;lady, pardon me&mdash;but you&mdash;I&mdash;my ma&s;ter&mdash;I wont leave him&mdash;I have it&mdash;hard by there's a mill, mention the name of Zarno, and you'll find protection <STAGE>(again looking out)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ro&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! guide us to it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, I'll walk a little way with you: there <STAGE>(walks a few yards then &s;tops)</STAGE> there now, that's the road, right along there <STAGE>(pointing one way, and looking another)</STAGE> good fortune attend you, lady! Oh, my unhappy ma&s;ter!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is it kept by one Wit&s;ki?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>It is.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>How lucky! an old friend of mine, that I made acquaintance with this morning.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh Zorin&s;ki! oh my ma&s;ter!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ro&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Zorin&s;ki! away&mdash;away&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Cur.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't droop, dear mi&s;tre&s;s; for tho' you have but one man to protect you, yet con|&s;ider, that one is an Iri&s;hman. <STAGE>[Exeunt Ro&s;olia and O'Curragh.]</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>What can this mean? &s;he afraid of him&mdash;Eh! here he comes again.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="57" REF="59"><HI>Enter</HI> ZORINSKI.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Will the hour never come? I'm glad my faithful Zarno left me&mdash;his fondne&s;s tore my heart &s;trings!&mdash;not gone&mdash;avaunt! I &s;ay&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't look &s;o terrible&mdash;oh, don't&mdash;you frighten me &s;o I can't go&mdash;oh, ma&s;ter, there is murder in your eye! if it were day light, I would not mind it&mdash;I &s;hould like to &s;ee you fight in day light: but none but a&s;&s;a&s;&s;ins &s;tab in the dark.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Horrid truth!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, ma&s;ter, quit this place; let us return to the dear dreary mine again! did not I hear the tread of hor&s;es? <STAGE>(agitated)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Look out!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, I will&mdash;but pray don't leave me. <STAGE>(more alarmed)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Look out, I &s;ay!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes; oh Lord!</P>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>My &s;en&s;es are benumbed&mdash;I'm very faint&mdash;but thy oath, thy oath, Zorin&s;ki! there I'm firm again.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ZARNO.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! dear ma&s;ter, all my fears are over.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who is it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pardon, dear Lord, what a rogue was I to think the great Zorin&s;ki could &s;werve from ho|nour&mdash;I feared it was &s;ome rival, or&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="58" REF="60">
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who is't? I &s;ay.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thank heaven, none that you can harm&mdash;it's the King. <STAGE>(with a &s;mile)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! <STAGE>(gra&s;ps his &s;word)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh God! oh ma&s;ter!&mdash;what&mdash;impo&s;|&s;ible&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Di&s;cord is at large&mdash;oh, for a tyger's fury&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(lays bold of his cloak)</STAGE> Oh! think a mo|ment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Cling not to me thus&mdash;away! I &s;ay. <STAGE>(Zarno runs round, and falls on his knees before him)</STAGE> villain!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, I am&mdash;any thing, reproach me, &s;purn me, kill me&mdash;Zorin&s;ki an a&s;&s;a&s;&s;in! <HI>my</HI> Lord a traitor! I can't bear it. Oh! think of di&s;|honour&mdash;think of your &s;oul&mdash;think of Zarno!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>In vain&mdash;in vain&mdash;were he guarded by the furies, I would &s;eize him! <HI>(as he is ru&s;hing for|ward, Zarno jumps back, draws his &s;word, and op|po&s;es him)</HI> ha! rai&s;e thy arm again&s;t thy ma&s;ter's life!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do not you rai&s;e your arm again&s;t your ma&s;ter's life.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, hell! he's right&mdash;Zarno, thou art &s;adly changed&mdash;I've &s;een thee draw to <HI>&s;ave</HI> my life.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>And now I draw to &s;ave what's dearer, your honour, your &s;oul&mdash;you pa&s;s not&mdash;no! I
<PB N="59" REF="61">
would rather &s;ee you dead at my feet, and I the man that laid you there; than &s;uffer you to pa&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Baffled by a &s;lave <STAGE>(cla&s;hing of &s;words with|out)</STAGE> ha! the work of death's begun; &s;ee how their &s;abres&mdash;gleam&mdash;brave not my fury&mdash;give way&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, by heaven! <STAGE>(with firmne&s;s)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hark! 'tis vengeance calls&mdash;then take thy death, vile &s;lave.&mdash; <STAGE>(fight, he wounds Zarno, and exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Heaven forgive him! let me but live to &s;ee&mdash; <STAGE>(&s;taggers to the &s;ide of the &s;tage, &s;upporting him|&s;elf on his &s;word)</STAGE> how dim my eyes are&mdash;ah! &s;ee he ru&s;hes among them; he bears down all before him&mdash;ah! now he &s;eizes the King, and now he&mdash;oh! <HI>(falls)</HI></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> RACHEL.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rac.</SPEAKER>
<P>What cla&s;hing of &s;words! oh! I &s;hall &s;ink with fear. Zarno! Zarno!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(faintly)</STAGE>
<P>Here.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rac.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh Zarno! bleeding!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, cruel ma&s;ter! cruel ma&s;ter!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rac.</SPEAKER>
<P>Was it he that did it? mon&s;ter! is this a return for a fond &s;ervant's love?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Did I &s;ay it was my ma&s;ter? did I? no Rachel, no.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rac.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come try to reach the mill, for poor Ra|chel's &s;ake try.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="60" REF="62">
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, I'll try, <STAGE>(ri&s;es)</STAGE> only this&mdash;you know Rachel, the words of a dying man are awful&mdash;then hear mine; it was not my ma&s;ter that did this&mdash;remember, Rachel, it was not my ma&s;ter. <STAGE>Exeunt, Rachel &s;upporting him.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE III&mdash;<HI>Another part of the Wood&mdash;Thun|der and Lightning.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ZORINSKI, <HI>pulling in</HI> CASIMIR.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>On! I charge thee.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>This wounded frame can go no farther.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now ye fiends, ye who fir&s;t in&s;tilled into my &s;oul your damning purpo&s;e, nerve but my arm to &s;trike the blow&mdash;<HI>(thunder)</HI> oh, God of ju&s;tice! why hurl thy bolts of fate to &s;care the peace|ful grove, when I &s;tand here a wretch and court the vengeful &s;haft? Hark! a noi&s;e again&mdash;delay were fatal&mdash;on, on, or here thou die&s;t!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here be it then&mdash;I tell thee ba&s;e a&s;&s;a&s;&s;in&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thou wrong'&s;t me, King&mdash;I am no com|mon &s;tabber&mdash;view me well&mdash;have the wrongs thou ha&s;t inflicted on me, &s;o furrowed o'er my vi&s;age, has de&s;pair &s;o grimly marked me for her own, that thou rememb're&s;t not? know then 'tis Zorin&s;ki &s;trikes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="61" REF="63">
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Zorin&s;ki&mdash;but oh, is't po&s;&s;ible&mdash;can thy &s;oul be reconciled to trea&s;on?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE>
<P>How that &s;hot thro' me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Art thou content, that future ages &s;hall u&s;e thy great name to cur&s;e with.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>My hair bri&s;tles, and my teeth chatter&mdash;peace I charge thee.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tho&s;e convul&s;ive throbs, &s;peak virtue in thee&mdash;oh, obey it's &s;acred impul&s;e&mdash;behold thy|&s;elf thy King's deliverer&mdash;&s;ee hands and hearts hail thee thy country's &s;aviour&mdash;think how the good will pray for thee, and ages ble&s;s thy name.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh let me with repentant&mdash;ha! is not the deadly oath &s;worn&mdash;hell I'm faithful to thee&mdash;who is't that holds my arm?&mdash; <STAGE>(a bugle is heard at a di&s;tance)</STAGE> Ha! again&mdash;now&mdash; <STAGE>(rai&s;ing his arm)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>A moment's pau&s;e&mdash;Oh God, &s;hield with thy arm omnipotent my dear, ill-fated Po|land; receive my parting &s;pirit, and, oh! for|give this man. Now, traitor, &s;trike.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(After a &s;truggle)</STAGE>
<P>Oh, impo&s;&s;ible! <STAGE>(falls at the King's feet, then recovers him&s;elf on his knee)</STAGE> Oh, Ca&s;imir&mdash;Oh my King&mdash;how &s;hall I look upon that injured face.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Zorin&s;ki, the fiery trial pa&s;t gives thee to my heart more pure&mdash; <STAGE>(a whi&s;tle)</STAGE> Hark, thy com|rades:</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="62" REF="64">
<SPEAKER>Zo. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Starts up and recovers his &s;word)</STAGE>
<P>Let them come on; this weight of guilt taken from this arm, I will protect thee, King&mdash;Virtue's electric fire &s;o &s;prings each nerve, that did nature loo&s;e her ravenous kind&mdash;did hell oppo&s;e its mini&s;ters of blood, I &s;eem as with one blow I could &s;weep them to de&s;truction.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'm faint&mdash;my wound begins to torture&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Horror! 'Twas not my &s;word&mdash;'twas not my &s;word, my King, that wounded thee; for, e'en in that guilty moment, I &s;truck the villain dead that did inflict it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Give me thy arm.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>See, the moon dares &s;hine again&mdash;Can'&s;t thou forgive me&mdash;thou may'&s;t, but can heaven?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>No more; thou ha&s;t unclogged thy &s;oul of trea&s;on; trea&s;on, that mo&s;t hideous murder, which, with one blow, &s;evers a nation's peace, tramples down law, that barrier of exi&s;tence, and gives to him mo&s;t triumph, who mo&s;t &s;hall murder and de|&s;troy. <STAGE>Exeunt, King leaning on Zorin&s;ki.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="4" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE IV.&mdash;<HI>A Mill.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> WITSKI <HI>from the Mill.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh dear, oh dear, I do &s;o overflow with joy, that I'm quite mi&s;erable. I can't eat, and I
<PB N="63" REF="65">
can't &s;leep&mdash;thank heaven, I can ju&s;t contrive to drink a little, el&s;e&mdash;what a rate my mill went all day&mdash;clack, clack, clack&mdash;Winny's tongue had no chance with it&mdash;and then to think of the &s;weet lady Ro&s;olia &s;eeking protection in my man|&s;ion&mdash;there's an honour&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zorin&s;ki</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(behind).</STAGE>
<P>Hollo!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>What! an enemy may be! Then, I'll re|tire into my ca&s;tle, and parley from the battle|ments. <STAGE>(goes in)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> CASIMIR <HI>and</HI> ZORINSKI.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Within there. <STAGE>(&s;trikes his &s;word again&s;t a window)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit&s;ki above.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stand off, or I've a cro&s;s-bow here mil &s;end a choice collection of bullets into your pate; break one of my windows, you rob|bers!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Give in&s;tant entrance, or I'll force my way.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>Know all men, I am lord of my ca&s;tle&mdash;have been &s;o&mdash;aye, thirteen hours, and will knock any man's brains out, that enters without my leave.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Are you lord of it? prove then you de|&s;erve the title, by giving &s;uccour to the unfortu|nate.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="64" REF="66">
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, there's no &s;tanding that. <STAGE>(comes down)</STAGE> You mu&s;t know I am lord of this&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Leave prating, and in&s;tant lend thy aid.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your King demands it&mdash; <STAGE>(Wit&s;ki drops on his knees)</STAGE> give me your a&s;&s;i&s;tance.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, no&mdash;Heaven forbid that I &s;hould dare to think of &s;uch a thing&mdash;Oh, no.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>I want not thy obedience, but thy &s;ervice; I faint for very wearine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ROSOLIA, O'CURRAGH, <HI>and</HI> WINIFRED, <HI>from the Mill.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ro&s;o.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sure that voice&mdash;heavenly powers! the King!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>With equal wonder I behold thee, fair maiden.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ro&s;o.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Sire, forgive me, if thus untimely I pre&s;s my private griefs&mdash;where is my lord? Oh, does Radzano live?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>E'en now we parted near your father's ca&s;tle.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ro&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>O'Curragh, fly. <STAGE>Exit O'Currah.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>But whether he live or no&mdash; <STAGE>(looks at Zo|rin&s;ki, who is agitated with &s;hame and remor&s;e)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ro&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh horror! he here!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fear not, wronged lady, the ba&s;ili&s;k has lo&s;t its power to harm.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lead me in. <STAGE>Exit with Ro&s;olia.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="65" REF="67">
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Faire&s;t innocent! and has this withering arm bla&s;ted thy joys&mdash;Oh, was not my agony enough before. How came &s;he here?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>Zarno &s;ent her; would you choo&s;e to walk in <STAGE>(goes towards the door)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Zarno! Zarno! <STAGE>(with vacant wildne&s;s)</STAGE> Soft&mdash;good brain collect thy&s;elf&mdash;&s;ure I &s;aw him in the fore&s;t&mdash;and he went&mdash;no&mdash;ah, now helli&s;h recollection darts upon me&mdash;he wept&mdash;he begged me&mdash;he clung to me, and I&mdash; <STAGE>(as if choaked with grief, makes the motion of &s;tabbing)</STAGE> Oh, I am deeply damned for that&mdash;the only &s;oul on earth that loved me&mdash;never &s;ervant &s;o loved a ma&s;ter&mdash; <STAGE>(weeps)</STAGE> and I to &s;tab, oh!&mdash;Eh&mdash;perhaps he yet lives perhaps&mdash;here &s;lave&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>I beg your pardon, Sir, but I am not a a &s;lave.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I care not what thou art.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Be dumb&mdash;mark&mdash;take this &s;word&mdash;guard well the door&mdash;I'll return anon&mdash;oh, Zarno, Zarno!</P>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>He's mad&mdash;the poor devil's mad.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Win.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now, my dear Wit&s;ki&mdash;I'll tell you what&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, you are beginning your chatter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Win.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, now, only hear me, that's a dear man. You know, hu&s;band, his Maje&s;ty has fa|voured us with his company at our hou&s;e; very
<PB N="66" REF="68">
well; then, you know, it will be but civil to re|turn the vi&s;it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>Certainly; he'll naturally expect it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Win.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well; and &s;o I was a thinking that &s;ome new fur put upon my Sunday's cap, with ro&s;e-co|loured ribbons, and my new ru&s;&s;et gown will do to&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ro&s;olia.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(within)</STAGE>
<P>What, miller, ho!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Stopping Winifred's month)</STAGE>
<P>You will keep gabble, gabble&mdash;confound you, is not his Maje&s;ty within hearing, and an't I his &s;word-bearer&mdash;hu&s;h&mdash;I mu&s;t guard the door&mdash;and, do you hear, keep the cats and the dogs quiet&mdash;hu&s;h, &s;oftly. <STAGE>Exeunt into the Mill.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="5" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE V.&mdash;<HI>Wood.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> RACHEL, <HI>leading in</HI> ZARNO.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rac.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, dear Zarno, &s;ee, yonder's the mill; you look better.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do I, Rachel?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rac.</SPEAKER>
<P>Far better, &s;ince with my hair I &s;topt the bleeding of your wound.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis not my wound, Rachel; its here, its here; my heart's broken, Rachel&mdash;Oh, my
<PB N="67" REF="69">
ma&s;ter&mdash;Let me re&s;t here awhile, it will give me &s;trength. <STAGE>(lies down)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ZORINSKI.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Zarno&mdash;alive&mdash; <STAGE>(runs to him, and kneels)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, Rachel, hide me&mdash;don't touch me&mdash;don't touch me&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>How art thou, Zarno? Shrink not from me&mdash;I come to comfort thee.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Comfort&mdash;&s;ay, then, <STAGE>(in a low tone, and getting near him)</STAGE> lives the King?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>What is that to thee? <STAGE>(Zarno &s;hrinks from him)</STAGE> he does! he does!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>What lives&mdash;lives&mdash;ha! ha! ha! <STAGE>(faints)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Soft, he recovers&mdash;how art thou Zarno?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Better&mdash;well&mdash;very well&mdash;but are you not deceiving me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, on my &s;oul&mdash;Zarno, I am not &s;o damned a villain as thou think'&s;t me. <STAGE>(with an agony of grief, hiding his face)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>I think you a villain! dear honoured ma&s;ter, where is your hand? <STAGE>(ki&s;&s;es it)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let me convey thee to a place of &s;afety.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>I can walk&mdash;can walk very well.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Art thou&mdash;art thou&mdash;much wounded Zarno? <STAGE>(with &s;hame)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rac.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh yes&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="68" REF="70">
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(&s;topping her).</STAGE>
<P>A &s;cratch&mdash;a &s;cratch&mdash;it's joy makes me &s;o weak&mdash;I'm very trouble&s;ome&mdash;I can walk alone.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;haw! re&s;t on me good fellow.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'm afraid I lean very heavily.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Prythee be quiet&mdash;&s;ee'&s;t thou that mill&mdash;the King is there&mdash;we &s;hall ea&s;ily reach it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>O yes, dear ma&s;ter, unle&s;s I die with joy by the way&mdash;I'm quite a&s;ham'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come re&s;t firmly on me&mdash;there&mdash;there.</P>
<STAGE>Exeunt.</STAGE>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="6" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE VI.&mdash;<HI>In&s;ide of the Mill.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE>CASIMIR <HI>di&s;covered a&s;leep on a Pallet,</HI> ROSOLIA <HI>watching him,</HI> WITSKI <HI>guarding the door.</HI></STAGE>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>SONG&mdash;</HEAD>
<SP>
<STAGE>WINIFRED.</STAGE>
<LG>
<L>THAN envied Monarchs happier &s;till,</L>
<L>O! happier far, the Pea&s;ant,</L>
<L>No trea&s;oh lurks around his mill,</L>
<L>No terror breaks his &s;lumbers plea&s;ant.</L>
<L>Yet one mu&s;t fill the regal &s;eat,</L>
<L>With care ince&s;&s;ant pre&s;&s;ing,</L>
<L>E'en to pre&s;erve tho&s;e &s;lumbers &s;weet,</L>
<L>His lowly, happy cottage, ble&s;&s;ing.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2">
<PB N="69" REF="71">
<HEAD>II.</HEAD>
<L>Then fly not now, O gentle &s;leep,</L>
<L>Fly not our humble dwelling,</L>
<L>His angui&s;h in oblivion &s;teep,</L>
<L>The image of the pa&s;t repelling.</L>
<L>And &s;uch &s;oft vi&s;ions of delight,</L>
<L>From airy fancy borrow,</L>
<L>As he de&s;erves, who&s;e watchful night</L>
<L>From us poor Pea&s;ants, drives forth &s;orrow,</L>
</LG>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<STAGE>A knocking at the Door.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(awakes)</STAGE>
<P>What refre&s;hing &s;leep&mdash;heaven accept my thanks&mdash;Ro&s;olia! droop'&s;t thou for thy love&mdash;fear not his &s;afety&mdash;have I not &s;een him in the field&mdash;believe me he mu&s;t be cham|pion indeed, who &s;poils Radzano&mdash;ho&s;te&s;s I thir&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Win.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here, your Maje&s;ty's, a cup of wine, all our poor hou&s;e affords.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Ca&s;imir is about to drink, when the knocking at the door is repeated.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Open good fellow&mdash;and fear nothing.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ZORINSKI <HI>and</HI> RACHEL, <HI>leading</HI> ZARNO.</STAGE>
<P>Poor wretch&mdash;he faints&mdash;lead me to him <STAGE>(ap|proaches Zarno, who looks faintly on him)</STAGE> here
<PB N="70" REF="72">
poor knave, drink this&mdash;thy wants far exceed mine&mdash;drink, 'twill refre&s;h thee.</P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh no!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do as I bid thee! <STAGE>(Zarno drinks)</STAGE> has't done thee good, knave?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh yes!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>And me abundant&mdash;come thou look'&s;t more cheerly&mdash;thou art better.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zar.</SPEAKER>
<P>Better! I never was &s;o well in my life.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ro&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>It grieves me in &s;uch ba&s;e &s;ort to &s;ee your highne&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not &s;o fair one&mdash;am I not with my people, with tho&s;e who love me&mdash;come mine ho&s;t&mdash;thy fire, <STAGE>(to Wit&s;ki)</STAGE> wilt thou to court and grow great? <STAGE>(&s;ighs and &s;hakes his head)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>Plea&s;e your Maje&s;ty&mdash;I can't leave my trade.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, knave?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>Becau&s;e I have a wife&mdash;and to confe&s;s the truth to your Maje&s;ty&mdash;Winny, has certainly a happy knack at &s;prightly conver&s;ation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(to Ro&s;olia &s;miling)</STAGE>
<P>Hear'&s;t thou the &s;landerer?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wit.</SPEAKER>
<P>So when &s;he lets her tongue go&mdash;I let my mill go, clack for clack&mdash;I could not manage without my mill.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! ha! I'll build thee one upon the Vi&s;tula&mdash;thou &s;halt be the greate&s;t miller in Poland. <STAGE>(trumpet without)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="71" REF="73"><HI>Enter</HI> RADZANO.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rad.</SPEAKER>
<P>My gracious King! <STAGE>(kneels)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>Radzano thrice welcome&mdash;&s;aid I not Ro|&s;olia, this arm would prove victorious.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ro&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>My deare&s;t lord!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rad.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pardon dear mi&s;tre&s;s, what &s;tern duty compells&mdash;Rodom&s;ko was found wandering in the fore&s;t, de&s;erted by his people.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ro&s;. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(kneeling to Ca&s;imir)</STAGE>
<P>Oh merciful Ca&s;imir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(rai&s;ing her)</STAGE>
<P>Fear nothing&mdash;let him live&mdash;but not in Poland.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rad.</SPEAKER>
<P>See, how your loving &s;ubjects, bearing their ru&s;tic arms, pre&s;s on to guard you.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter Soldiers and Pea&s;ants armed.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;.</SPEAKER>
<P>What a proud moment&mdash;heaven give me &s;trength to bear this ru&s;hing joy&mdash;tru&s;t me, my people, the dangers I have pa&s;&s;ed will but give energy to fre&s;h exertion&mdash;yes, like the fertilizing Vi&s;tula, mild yet irre&s;i&s;tible, I'll open wide the cur|rent of my ju&s;tice, until the humble&s;t pea&s;ant of my &s;tate &s;hall ta&s;te it's ble&s;&s;ings.</P>
</SP>
<Q><PB N="72" REF="74">
<TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>FINALE.</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHORUS OF SOLDIERS.</SPEAKER>
<L>Let the loud rattling drum and the trumpet's &s;hrill clang,</L>
<L>That in battle our heroes have nerved;</L>
<L>Now aid the rough &s;oldier in rapturous &s;ong,</L>
<L>For his King and his country pre&s;erved.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>PEASANTS.</SPEAKER>
<LG>
<L>Let the happy pea&s;ant join,</L>
<L>And his humble lay combine,</L>
<L>While joy in every face &s;hall &s;hine,</L>
<L>Throughout the realm of Poland.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Every hone&s;t tongue &s;hall &s;ing,</L>
<L>Every happy valley ring,</L>
<L>For Heaven has re&s;tor'd our King,</L>
<L>And happine&s;s to Poland.</L>
</LG>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ZARNO.</SPEAKER>
<L>Ble&s;&s;ed with Peace and Liberty,</L>
<L>My life &s;hall pa&s;s in merry glee,</L>
<L>With little Zarnos on my knee,</L>
<L>And Rachel dear &s;o clever.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="73" REF="75">
<SPEAKER>WINIFRED and RACHEL.</SPEAKER>
<L>Should our artle&s;s &s;tory move,</L>
<L>And you, our valued friends approve,</L>
<L>With warme&s;t gratitude and love,</L>
<L>We are your &s;laves for ever.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHORUS.</SPEAKER>
<L>Let the happy Pea&s;ant, &amp;c.</L>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
